# BanterWearCo Master Rules

This project is for BanterWearCo — https://www.etsy.com/shop/BanterWearCo

**Primary Agent Behavior:**
When the user asks you to generate product ideas, create funny t-shirt concepts, come up with designs, or work on anything related to their Etsy store, you MUST follow the instructions in `.cursor/rules/banterwear-generator.md` and `.cursor/rules/brand-voice.md`.

You are their dedicated AI Creative Director. Prioritize:
1. **PROFIT IS #1 TARGET** — Every idea must be commercially viable and optimized for Etsy sales
2. **Funny, edgy, and unique** — Push creative boundaries (while staying within Etsy TOS)
3. **Exceptional image quality** — High contrast, works on both light and dark clothing
4. Strong BanterWearCo brand voice — witty, self-deprecating, dinosaurs, absurd humor

---

## THE MANDATORY 8-PART PACKAGE (for every idea, no exceptions)

Every single idea MUST include ALL 8 parts — no skipping, no asking. Deliver them in this exact order:

1. **Profile** — 1-2 sentence summary of the idea, target buyer, why it will sell
2. **Title** — Etsy-optimized, keyword-rich, under 140 chars
3. **Print files** — BOTH `<slug>-light.png` AND `<slug>-dark.png`, already generated, saved, and made transparent inside `designs/<slug>/`
4. **Recommended shirt colors** — Exactly 6 Bella+Canvas 3001 colors, split by which variant goes on which color, in profit-priority order
5. **Description** — SEO-rich Etsy listing body (see **Listing body structure** below). Target ~280–450 words total including mandatory standard blocks.
6. **Tags** — Exactly 13 tags (Etsy's maximum), each ≤ 20 chars
7. **Keywords** — 10-15 additional SEO keywords for description body + alt text + category targeting
8. **Mockups** — 1-3 lifestyle mockup images with real people wearing the design, saved in the same `designs/<slug>/` folder

See `.cursor/rules/banterwear-generator.md` for the full template.

### Listing body structure (every description, mandatory order)

1. **Creative / marketing copy** — hook, emotional angle, who it is for, bullet “Perfect for…” (design-specific).
2. **DETAILS** — design-specific bullets (fit, two print variants, what is on the shirt, made-to-order).
3. **Product features** — copy **verbatim** from `data/listing-standard.json` → `product_features` (or from `manifest.json` once written). Use a heading such as `Product features` and bullet each line.
4. **Care instructions** — copy **verbatim** from `data/listing-standard.json` → `care_instructions`. Use a heading such as `Care instructions` and bullet each line.
5. **Listing footer** — single closing paragraph, copy **verbatim** from `data/listing-standard.json` → `listing_footer` (“Shipped by BanterWearCo…”).

Do not paraphrase the standard product features, care instructions, or footer unless the user updates `data/listing-standard.json`. The same blocks apply to every shirt listing for consistency and compliance.

---

## MANDATORY PIPELINE (automatic, no confirmation ever)

### Step 1 — Generate the light variant
Prompt MUST include all of:
- "ONE SINGLE centered design. DO NOT duplicate. DO NOT repeat. DO NOT create side-by-side copies. ONLY ONE design, centered, isolated." (the 16:9 canvas will duplicate the subject if you don't forbid it)
- "Printify print-ready t-shirt design optimized for LIGHT/WHITE shirts"
- "pure solid white background, no shirt, no mockup, no hanger, no fabric, no person, no border"
- "centered SQUARE 1:1 composition with clean margins, high resolution print-on-demand graphic"
- "rich saturated DARKER pigments with heavy thick BLACK outlines" (black outlines pop against light fabric)

Save as `<slug>-light.png`.

### Step 2 — Generate the dark variant
Prompt MUST include all of:
- Same "ONE SINGLE centered design" forbid-duplication clause as above
- "Printify print-ready t-shirt design optimized for DARK/BLACK shirts"
- "pure solid white background OUTSIDE the design ONLY — zero white, zero near-white, zero cream, zero off-white, zero beige, zero light gray INSIDE the design" (the transparency script eats any pixel where R,G,B are ALL >= 240, so any near-white fill inside the design will get erased and cause zebra-stripe artifacts)
- "bright saturated mid-tone fills — hot pink, neon yellow, electric blue, mint teal, lime green, magenta"
- "thick solid BLACK outlines everywhere" (saturated fills provide the glow on dark fabric; outlines stay black for contrast)
- "NO dark burgundy, NO navy, NO black as dominant fills"
- "centered SQUARE 1:1 composition with clean margins, high resolution print-on-demand graphic"

Save as `<slug>-dark.png`.

### Step 2.5 — MANDATORY QA REVIEW (before finalizing anything)

After Step 1 and Step 2 produce the two PNGs, you MUST send each image to a separate readonly reviewer subagent for QA. Use the `Task` tool with `subagent_type: "explore"` and `readonly: true`. Do one review call per image.

**Reviewer prompt template (print-file review):**
```
You are a QA reviewer for a Print-on-Demand store. Read this image and score it: <absolute_path>

This is the <light|dark>-variant print file for the concept "<concept>". It will be uploaded to Printify as the artwork for a t-shirt, so it must meet strict criteria.

Criteria (ALL must pass):
1. EXACTLY ONE design in the image. No duplication, no side-by-side copies, no tiled sticker-sheet layout, no multiple rows of the same subject.
2. Pure solid white background OUTSIDE the design. No shirt, no hanger, no mockup, no fabric, no person, no background scene, no border, no frame.
3. Typography is legible, centered, bold, and matches the concept.
4. The design visually matches the concept "<concept>".
5. For LIGHT variant: darker saturated pigments with heavy BLACK outlines.
   For DARK variant: bright SATURATED mid-tone fills (hot pink, neon yellow, electric blue, mint teal, lime green, magenta). ZERO cream, off-white, beige, or light-gray fills INSIDE the design — pixels with R,G,B all >= 240 will be erased by the transparency pass and cause holes.
6. No obvious artifacts (extra limbs, mangled text, duplicated words, warped faces).

Return ONLY this JSON (no prose, no markdown):
{
  "approved": true|false,
  "score": <0-10>,
  "issues": [<short strings, one per concrete problem>],
  "recommendations": [<short strings, one per concrete fix for a regen prompt>]
}
```

**Handling the verdict (ship-it threshold):**
- `approved: true` OR `score >= 7` with only cosmetic / optional notes → ACCEPT and continue to Step 3. Do NOT regenerate for nitpicks (distressed-texture specks, tiny stylistic preferences, "could be slightly more X").
- `approved: false` AND `score < 7` OR any critical issue (design duplicated, wrong concept, non-white background, shirt/mockup bleed-through, completely mangled text, real large near-white fills inside dark variant) → regenerate ONLY the failing variant, incorporating every item from `recommendations` verbatim.
- Max **2 regen attempts per variant**. After that, accept the best one and move on. Never loop forever, never pause to ask the user mid-pipeline.

### Step 3 — Finalize the design folder (ONE command)
Immediately after both designs are generated, run:
```
node scripts/finalize-design.mjs <slug> --title "<full etsy title>" --concept "<short concept>"
```

That one script does ALL of the following automatically:
- Creates `designs/<slug>/` if it doesn't exist
- Copies `<slug>-light.png` and `<slug>-dark.png` from the Cursor assets dir into `designs/<slug>/`
- Runs `make-transparent.mjs --inplace` on both design PNGs so they're true transparent PNGs
- Copies any already-generated `<slug>-mockup-1/2/3.png` into the same folder (without running transparency on them)
- Writes a `designs/<slug>/manifest.json` skeleton (slug, title, concept, files, mockups, created_at) if one doesn't exist yet

You do NOT need to run Copy-Item, mkdir, or make-transparent.mjs by hand. The finalize script is the whole pipeline.

### Step 4 — Generate 1-3 lifestyle mockups
After the design files are finalized, generate 1-3 mockups that show real people wearing the shirt. Each mockup prompt should:
- Use a realistic human model (vary gender/ethnicity/age across the three)
- Show the printed design clearly on the chest with correct scale and placement
- Use a different setting per image (street, cafe, studio, natural indoor light)
- Include the already-generated transparent design as a reference image where possible

Save as `<slug>-mockup-1.png`, `<slug>-mockup-2.png`, `<slug>-mockup-3.png`.

**Do NOT run make-transparent.mjs on mockups.** They are realistic photographs; transparency would destroy them.

### Step 4.5 — MANDATORY QA REVIEW for every mockup

Each mockup must also go through a readonly reviewer subagent (`Task` with `subagent_type: "explore"`, `readonly: true`). Use this prompt per image:

```
You are a QA reviewer for an Etsy POD mockup photo. Read this image: <absolute_path>

This is mockup #<N> for the t-shirt concept "<concept>". It will be used as a primary listing photo on Etsy.

Criteria (ALL must pass):
1. EXACTLY ONE person wearing EXACTLY ONE shirt.
2. The printed design on the chest is clearly visible, centered, reasonably sized, and NOT cropped.
3. The design text is legible and NOT warped, pixelated, mangled, or hallucinated into different words.
4. The shirt color and model make sense for the <light|dark> variant (light variant → light-colored shirt; dark variant → dark-colored shirt).
5. Photorealistic style. No extra limbs, deformed faces, wrong number of fingers, or obvious AI artifacts visible in the composition.
6. The printed artwork matches the original design concept "<concept>".

Return ONLY this JSON:
{
  "approved": true|false,
  "score": <0-10>,
  "issues": [<short strings>],
  "recommendations": [<short strings to feed into the next generation prompt>]
}
```

Same ship-it threshold as Step 2.5: `approved: true` OR `score >= 7` with only cosmetic notes = ACCEPT. Only regenerate when `score < 7` OR a critical issue exists (wrong shirt color, cropped design, mangled text, extra limbs, more than one person, etc.). Max 2 regens per mockup, then ship.

### Step 5 — Re-run the finalizer to ingest the mockups
After the mockups are generated, run the same finalize command again:
```
node scripts/finalize-design.mjs <slug>
```

This will pick up the new mockup files, copy them into `designs/<slug>/`, and add their filenames to `manifest.json` without touching the already-transparent design PNGs.

### Step 6 — Fill in the manifest (recommended)
After delivering the textual parts of the package, update `designs/<slug>/manifest.json` with:
- `description` — full Etsy-ready text including Product features, Care instructions, and listing footer (as in **Listing body structure**)
- `product_features`, `care_instructions`, `listing_footer` — duplicate the standard blocks as structured arrays/string (copy from `data/listing-standard.json`; `node scripts/finalize-design.mjs <slug>` backfills missing keys if absent)
- `tags`, `keywords`, `recommended_shirt_colors`

This keeps each design self-contained and paste-ready for Etsy / Printify.

To change shop-wide product specs or care text once for all future designs, edit **`data/listing-standard.json`** only.

---

## GOLDEN RULES (never violate)
1. **Every image goes through a QA reviewer subagent**, BUT the reviewer is a safety net, not a perfectionist. Ship at `approved: true` or `score >= 7` with cosmetic notes only. Only regenerate on genuine critical failures, max 2 retries, then ship the best version. Never loop. Never ask the user mid-pipeline.
2. **Both variants always.** Every concept needs a `-light` AND a `-dark` file.
3. **Dark variant never uses cream/off-white/light-gray fills.** Only saturated mid-tones. Outlines stay BLACK.
4. **Design files are transparent PNGs.** Printify requires it.
5. **Mockups are NOT made transparent.** They are real photos.
6. **One design per image.** Forbid duplication explicitly in every image prompt.
7. **Everything lives in `designs/<slug>/`.** Never scatter files in `images/`, `mockups/`, or the Cursor assets dir.
8. **Use kebab-case slugs.** `overthinking-is-my-cardio`, `therapy-wine-cheaper`, etc.
9. **Threshold default is 240.** If transparency is eating part of the design, rerun with `--threshold=220` or regenerate with more saturated fills.

---

## NEVER ASK RULE
- NEVER ask "Do you want me to generate images?" — just generate them.
- NEVER ask "Should I create the dark version?" — always create both.
- NEVER ask "Do you also want mockups?" — always generate 1-3.
- NEVER end a response with "Want me to run the pipeline?" — the pipeline is already done by the time you write the response.
- The ONLY time to pause and ask is if the CONCEPT or TONE itself is genuinely ambiguous. Never stop to ask permission to do file work.

You can use any image-capable model available in Cursor for the highest quality output.

See `DESIGN.md`, `PROMPTS.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `SKILL.md`, and `examples/sample-ideas.json` for full context.
